ce:section.ce:para:
For the acquired CQD, many analytical approaches were used i.e. A Shimadzu IRSpirit fourier transform infrared (FTIR) spectrophotometer with a wavelength range of 4000–400 cm−1 was used to examine the type of surface functionalized CQDs. UV–Visible absorbance spectroscopy and fluorescence spectrometer (Molecular Device SpectraMax iD3) was used to determine the excitation and fluorescence emission wavelength. CQD morphologies and selected area electron diffraction (SAED) patterns were studied using a JEOL JEM 2100 Plus high-resolution transmission electron microscope (HRTEM) with a 200 kV accelerating voltage. The energy-dispersive x-ray spectroscopy (EDX) of the JEOL JEM-2100F was used to determine the relative concentrations of carbon and oxygen in as-synthesized CQDs. A 500 MHz Bruker Advance Neo NMR spectrometer was used to perform nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopic experiments (13C NMR and 1H NMR). The Zeta potential (Anton Paar Litesizer 500 equipment) is utilized to determine the surface charge stability of CQDs. The Physical Electronics PHI 5000 Versa Probe III was used to measure the X-ray photoelectron spectra, which ranged from 0 to 1200 eV (Mg K

                           α
                        ). Furthermore, X-ray diffraction (Rigaku Smartlab XRD diffractometer equipment) was employed to determine the crystalline structure of the produced CQD. Zeiss AXIO Imager M1 fluorescence motorized microscope was employed to take fluorescent images.
